{"product_id": "48190", "page": 5, "page_order": 3, "recommended": false, "date": "2018-01-08", "text": "A somewhat disappointing sequel - the Assassin's Creed walking simulator. Assassin's Creed Brotherhood takes place right after Assassin's Creed II. Despite the exciting intro sequence at The Villa Auditore, the rest of the game slowly loses it's momentum. I love the newly added chain kills, summoning recruited assassins to help in combat at any time, and the beautiful graphics. However, the game does a terrible job with transitions. A majority of the time you will be walking alongside your allies enduring boring dialogue or chasing a target you can't assassinate. Also, there's just enough bugs and glitches in this game to become a noticeable annoyance.\nOverall, there were few moments in this game that made me smile (like the dialogue between Desmond and Lucy), but not enough to justify the playthrough. I'd recommend watching all of the cutscenes on youtube and just save yourself the money. There's not a whole lot you'll be missing out on.", "hours": 24.8, "username": "Anthony95", "products": 46, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 5, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-06", "text": "The best entry in the Ezio triliogy.  You're an unstoppable killing machine thanks to the chain kill mechanic and having recruits at your disposal is a great addition.  Story isnt as deep as the previous entry but still plenty enticing to want to see it through.  Romulus story and temples are a bit awkward from the story perspective but provide a good refresher to the assassin tombs.", "hours": 19.5, "username": "xxerichshxx", "products": 133, "early_access": false}
