{"product_id": "48190", "page": 103, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-10-06", "text": "At first, I was confused with the multiplayer addition \u2013 I thought all those awesome guys on the cover are to be assassins, alas, they are your targets in singleplayer portion of the game. Despite this, the real brotherhood was something new and experimental. As usual, I would list the best points from the game:\nIn my opinion, this game has the weakest soundtrack from the series, save for some tracks, it is quite repetitive (I believe this is due to the fact that we are in the same city and the need to differentiate does not arise).\nAlso, because of unknown reasons (only in Steam version), two missions are bugged - the final mission, unable to interact with Cesare after climbing the siege tower, and locked controls during flying the bomber. Don't know if I am the only one who encountered this problem.\nStill, it is a good sequel to Ezio story, recommend it.", "hours": 19.7, "username": "Hlelia", "products": 72, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 103, "page_order": 7, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-10-05", "text": "I would have loved to be able to play this game, but I can't even get it to start. Not from the uplay launcher, steam launcher, or even the game file it self..it just does not want to start up. I can get assassin's creed 2 to start, but this one..no. maybe you'll have better luck with getting this game to launch..from what I have read I'm not the only person to have this issue..PC Master race..I don't think so..not when we get screwd more then PS or Xbox with it comes to buggs erros, or crashes..hell look at batman arkham knight. and the five min's it says I have played..well that's all trying to get the damn thing to work..and it don't", "hours": 0.1, "user_id": "76561198098565770", "username": "Morgan Layfay", "products": 169, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 103, "page_order": 8, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-10-04", "text": "Could not get any asscreed game to run on windows 10. Googled around, it's a common problem. Ubisoft does not officially support windows 10.\nThis game installs another launcher (ubisoft launcher), and I believe it requires an internet connection.\nUbisoft is everything wrong with PC gaming. Never giving them another dime.", "hours": 26.3, "username": "Traches", "products": 227, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 103, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-10-04", "text": "This is a Good game. As an example, I present that I have purchased this game twice: once for console (and then the disc disappeared, fortunately after I'd already beaten it), and once now on Steam.\nIn some ways the game feels more like an expansion to AC2 than a full game in it's own right, but you get enough done over the course of the game that it stands on it's own fairly well.\nMy only real complaint is that this is really where Ubisoft started to listen to the fans complaints about the Meta-Plot. Yeah,  you get to explore Ezio's home, but it really feels like there was going to be more to it and they just never got around to doing it.\nIs this canonically part of the 40K universe? Well, it takes place on Terra, so in the broad since it certainly could be. Minerva, Jupiter and crew could easily be Eldar screwing around with early man, and the Apple and other artifacts would be Eldar tech.", "hours": 28.9, "username": "rickvoid", "products": 291, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 104, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-10-03", "text": "A step up from Assassin\u2019s Creed II, The city of Rome comes to life in incredible detail. Animations and character models are beautiful. Controls are nearly identical to previous iterations of the franchise, although combat mechanics have been greatly improved. Fans of the last game will notice some familiar tunes, but the score as a whole suits the action well. Voice acting is solid. With the new ability to switch between memories, a plethora of side-missions, and an engaging multiplayer component, there is no shortage of content here.", "hours": 13.3, "username": "ZS-KEV", "products": 168, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 104, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-10-01", "text": "Brotherhood... where do I start, So a about 20 minutes ago I wrote a review on AC2, if I where you I would read that and then read this. ACB took everything that was good about AC2 and added a little more, the world no longer has multiple cities and takes place only in Rome. A new mechanic has been added where the player can save citizens kind of like in AC1, after saving the citizen they can be added to the Assassin's guild. These assassin recruits can be summoned in combat. ACB has a slow story in the begining, but as the story heats up it gets better. I'm kind of bored so I'm gonna stop writing, its a great game so get it\n10/10\nEDIT: oh and it added muliplayer", "hours": 129.5, "user_id": "76561198131927486", "username": "Albert", "products": 88, "early_access": false}
