{"product_id": "48190", "page": 128, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-03-15", "text": "In some ways, Brotherhood is a lesser game than its predecessor, Assassin's Creed 2. It feels like a step back limiting the majority of the action to just one city (in this case Rome) instead of a larger portion of Italy. The game makes up for this by introducing more sandbox mechanics. It's also the first title in the series where you get to command Assassin Recruits and get them to help you in combat. It feels like less of a full title and more of an expansion for the second game in both length and scope, but this doesn't stop it from being worth your time.", "hours": 34.1, "username": "PaulP", "products": 666, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 128, "page_order": 4, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-03-15", "text": "Tons of terrible glitches, the story all goes to\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665 weird looking characters and animations, bad glitchy gameplay, all around bad game, even though the mechanics are interesting.  But yea, the mechanics were interesting 2 games ago.  Stop running this franchise into the ground.", "hours": 22.6, "username": "Bartholomew Cubbins", "products": 228, "early_access": false}
