{"product_id": "48190", "page": 141, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-01-01", "text": "This is a great game. I would reccomend playing AC II first so you can wrap your head around the story line, Ac I also being a good starting point. However this game runs much smoother on console and if you have the chance to play it on that platform first, do so.", "hours": 19.0, "user_id": "76561198121300621", "username": "cocainepapi", "products": 15, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 141, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-01-01", "text": "Framerate stability issues aside, this game plays very well on PC and looks by far better than its console siblings.  Not as vast as AC II, but still a great game.", "hours": 79.8, "user_id": "76561197970527145", "username": "Jedah", "products": 265, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 142, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-01-01", "text": "If you've played Assassins Creed 1 or 2, you'll feel at home in Brotherhood. This game feels more like an expansion pack to Assassins Creed 2 than an entire new game though. There's reused character models and animations galore. And unlike an expansion, you start back at ground zero with all your equipment burning so you have to re-earn it.\nSimilarities aside, Rome is a cool city, and calling in fellow assassins to help fight is when the game gets good. Don't bother trying to fully grasp the storyline, just know that the bad guys are taking over and it's up to you and your merry band of Assassins to stop them.\nI grabbed it on a steam sale for $4.99 and it was worth it for the gameplay and overarcing Assassins Creed storyline.\nPros:\n- Merry band of assassins makes bigger fights easy.\n- Owning shops and landmarks makes moneymaking simple.\n- Stab everything, you're an assassin.\nCons:\n- Muddled story - the Borgias are a generic evil family and Ezio has a lot of opportunities to kill members of the family and doesn't do it.\n- I feel like owning a shop or landmark should make me even more money.\n- Aside from the merry band of assassins, there isn't much new in the game.\nJust Weird\n- Horses galloping through crowds don't kill people.\n- At the start of the game you lose your equipment and the game has you rebuying it. But you also lose your ability to jump when climbing....because you lost it? Because I know Ezio learned how to do it in Assassins Creed 2, but you have to re-learn it in Assassins Creed Brotherhood.", "hours": 24.5, "username": "WhoIsMatt", "products": 570, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 142, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-01-01", "text": "Requires UPLAY.", "hours": 0.6, "username": "theUNCHARTED", "products": 169, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 142, "page_order": 2, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-01-01", "text": "If you expect it to work perfectly normal on Mac, it does not.\nNot for me at least.", "hours": 2.0, "username": "ToastSky", "products": 144, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 142, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-01-01", "text": "AC Brotherhood is the sequel to the highly regarded Assassins Creed 2. While they didn't reinvent the wheel with this game, they certainly improved and enhanced it.\nRather than the game taking place in multiple cities across Italy, AC:B takes place mostly in the city of Rome. However, Rome is by far the most detailed location in the game up to this point. You can upgrade local buisinesses in the world, take out guard outposts and burn them to the ground, and  run a local assassin guild you build from the ground up. Among many other things. The game is also noticeably harder and basically expects that you already played through AC2 before this one. It also features V/R missions like Metal Gear Solid so you can test your skills in the combat and stealth challenges. There's plenty to do in this game and the focus on side content is very noticeable.\nSo if you liked AC2, AC:B is the next thing to check out. On the other hand if you haven't played AC2, or didn't really like it I don't recommend this one. It expects that you have already played through AC2 and apart from the setting and the inclusion of a few new weapons it's virtually the same game.", "hours": 11.0, "username": "Silly/byte/", "products": 585, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 142, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-01-01", "text": "The first two in the AC series are good, but this game is what makes the series great. The gameplay, tons of side missions and content, new additions to weaponry, great puzzling bonus locations, the backstory... they're all well done. Don't hesitate to grab this one, especially on sale.", "hours": 69.2, "user_id": "76561198044852743", "username": "josiah.merola", "products": 13, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 142, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-12-31", "text": "This is what i call Assassins creed , not the new unity\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665. I enjoyed playing brotherhood way more than playing unity...\nAlso , Da Vinci ...\n10/10", "hours": 29.1, "username": "UndeadElite", "products": 170, "found_funny": 11, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 142, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-12-30", "text": "This game is, hands-down, the best AC game in the Ezio trilogy given the vast range of different activities you can get involved in. Thanks to it's predecessor in ACII, the mechanics in this one are very polished and it's reasonably easy to complete, but very difficult to complete completely.", "hours": 105.2, "username": "O61469", "products": 518, "early_access": false}
