{"product_id": "48190", "page": 143, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-12-29", "text": "The second Assassin's Creed title I've played.  The core mechanics remain the same, which in most cases is a mixed blessing.  In this case I think it worked out for the best, since the level design and a handful of new mechanics encouraged me to try out new tactics I hadn't attempted in the previous game.  In particular I made much use of the crossbow, poison darts, and minion attacks, the combination of which allowed me to take on much larger groups of guards without losing health.  As a strategic minded player, I greatly enjoyed leveling up my minions by sending them on missions.\nI spent 24 hours on the game, and overall I think I got my moneys worth.\n8/10", "hours": 24.4, "user_id": "76561198014931005", "username": "Puzzlebox", "products": 668, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 143, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-12-28", "text": "Third installment of the Assassin`s Creed Franchise. It's an open-world third person action adventure. As in AC2 you play as Enzio in italy around 1500 ac.\n+\nGraphics and Sound are top-notch\nAs in AC2 there are climbing puzzles which are fun\n-\nBoth story are really boring and the Desmond part ends up with a HUGE cliffhanger\nYou are collecting stuff, buy stores and build up stuff for no good reason\nThe fractions are pointless. I did not need \u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665s, soldiers or thieves for anything\nThere is no connection to the assassins you trained. You send them to a random city and they will get XP for that. In the game you can mark an enemy and they will kill him and disappear. It's like an autokill function", "hours": 21.5, "username": "Narrenfeste", "products": 368, "early_access": false}
