{"product_id": "48190", "page": 156, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-11-17", "text": "Assassin's creed pimp xD", "hours": 117.0, "user_id": "76561198042048703", "username": "Narsan", "products": 146, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 156, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-11-16", "text": "The third game in the Assassin's franchise, Brotherhood, introduces Ezio to well uhm the Brotherhood! The first few games of the franchise are the best in my own opinion, as they introduce a very interesting and different approach to the everyday game. Brotherhood stands out to its predecessors due to the fact that you can train other assassins and send them out to do missions.\n\nInteresting storyline with real life-inspired facts\nParkour and freerunning over the roofs or Rome\nGreat progression of protagonist (he 'ages' as you play)\nStill has the Assassin's Creed vibe to it\nThe Uplay business is bearable but quite annoying\nNo Steam Achievements\nNo Trading Cards (Emotes/Backgrounds)\nSome missions can be really frustrating", "hours": 23.4, "username": "My\u271ahical", "products": 995, "found_funny": 3, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 156, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-11-16", "text": "Elements from ACII are carried to this game and the story continues with a little more of everything. This time around, the player feels more included in the Assassin band because you could send in a team at your command. The story is as interesting as ACII if not a little less, because the game tries to answer everyone's questions, both the audience and Ezio's. There are a few more gadgets and a brotherhood, otherwise that is it. The gameplay is basically the same as in ACII. By the end of ACII, Ezio got a bit comfortable, but right from the beginning of this game, it is clear that there are other powers out there that are constantly uprising. As usual, the game design is beautiful. The city of Italy has a lot to take in with many areas to explore. The missions are roughly the same as in ACII, but there are a few new ones that were refreshing. This iteration of the series was not as amazing as ACII, but was still a fun game to experience.\nThe developers played it a bit safe by just using the same formula from the previous game. I enjoyed the sense of 'Brotherhood' when interaction with the assassin family in the game. I thought that the addition of the crossbow was awesome, and on top of that the arrow storm proved to be very useful in many situations that I encountered.\nAlthough there was a good amount of features added to the game, I did not get the same sense of awe throughout the game.", "hours": 14.1, "username": "LeClassified", "products": 88, "early_access": false}
