{"product_id": "48190", "page": 157, "page_order": 9, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-11-08", "text": "I'm going to review this as a PC game. This review is based on my experience of buying the PC version of this game, and not about what the game offers itself, simply because I have not had the chance to truly play it.\nI do not recommend this game on PC. When buying it on Steam, you will be redirected to a software called: \"Uplay\"\nEverytime this program tries to open the game up, it crashes. It won't even update, because it crashes before you have a chance to. I recommend buying this on PS3 or Xbox 360.", "hours": 8.5, "username": "Maxtez [FO]", "products": 139, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 158, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-11-06", "text": "I originally skipped this AC game since I felt it didn't wrap the Ezio storyline when it was released, and I only got it since it was on special.\nGiven that I payed little for it, I felt that I got my money's worth. This game doesn't add much to the AC story, but Ezio is one of the coolest assassins in the franchise and it was a blast to play through another adventure as him.\nThe gameplay of AC2 before it were polished to a tee in this game, and the new features allowing you to hire assassins, level them up, and call them in for assists was pretty cool. Taking over the new city 'Rome', purchasing buildings, and restoring it to its former glory was cool as well.\nAssassin's Creed - Brotherhood is pretty fun if you're a fan of the franchise, you can find it for cheap, and you have some time to burn.", "hours": 20.0, "user_id": "76561198063281813", "username": "InsanityWolf", "products": 125, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 158, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2014-11-06", "text": "Assassin's Creed: Brotherhood ultimately is another Assassin's Creed game. These games sit on the borderline between recommendation and non-recommendation for me; they're okay games, and do solid enough stuff, but also contain an unpleasantly large amount of tedium in them which isn't much fun. Some of the missions are solid, some of them are boring, and overall the game is kind of variable in how good it is over its length.\nI don't really regret playing these games, but it is hard to really recommend them either, as while the conspiracy ideas underpinning the game are neat, and the game is cool in places, there's a lot of time spent doing things which just aren't very interesting.\nOverall grade: C", "hours": 48.3, "username": "TheTitaniumDragon", "products": 1160, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 158, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2014-11-05", "text": "I love this series. Love it. I like the fact that history coincides with the Assassin v Templar storyline, which is not completely fictitious either. Brotherhood protrays Rome quite well, and has a fantastic storyline. Even with Unity on the horizon, I consider this my favorite game in the series.", "hours": 8.6, "username": "0bsol3te", "products": 173, "early_access": false}
