{"product_id": "48190", "page": 214, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-10-20", "text": "Compared to it's previous part, AC: Brotherhood blew my mind. The marvelous storyline, of which many things were not seen as coming, the lovable characters with their stories can catch anyone's heart. Title beautifully optimised, even for lower performance machines - and even that does not take the beauty of graphics in it.\nDefinite must-have for fans of hours of challenging gameplay and good plot-twisted storylines, accompanied by even more beautiful OST.", "hours": 44.3, "username": ".Me\u00d8w~", "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 214, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-10-20", "text": "This game is better than it's predecessors in certain ways and worse in others. The shadow war between the Assassins and Templars seems to be happening in the public now, with Rome knowing about the Assassins.\nThe story is the most simplistic in the series to date, and the main villain the same. Luckily the side characters are more actively developed and featured, and Ezio is shown as a leader, but we don't really see his development into that role.\nThe gameplay, however, has been improved from the last entry into the series, with combat being more fluid and the side missions correlating more into the story.\nIn this game you finally get a place to free-roam around as Desmond in, although it's small, but he also gets an interesting sequence at the end of the game.\n89/100", "hours": 135.5, "username": "Jexx", "products": 211, "early_access": false}
