{"product_id": "48190", "page": 223, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-03-16", "text": "Great game, great battle experiences. I love the recruiting-ability. One minus about this game is perhaps the fact that the story is soooo short. I went through the whole story in les than 20 hours. Nevertheless, has to be the best franchise I've ever played.", "hours": 36.4, "username": "0snak1n", "products": 51, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 223, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-03-10", "text": "...", "hours": 25.3, "user_id": "76561198042282293", "username": "K\u00e1\u010dko", "products": 198, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 223, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-03-06", "text": "When compared to AC2, Sisterhood to a large extent is more of the same, although it brings back some elements from AC1 (flags, begging women, citizens tackling enemies, occasional trips out of animus to read other people's emails) and adds new things, too (most importantly, you're getting to be head of assassin's guild in single player campaing; and yes, there's multiplayer added).\nInstead of segmentation into many smaller cities though, the majority of the action is on one huge map (Rome) with heaps of side missions to chose from at any single moment so it has more sandboxy feeling.\nI actually liked this more than AC2. Mostly due to this game having more actual \"game\" in it. Gamification is above all present in the missions that sport an additional requirement for 100%ing it. Sometimes it gives real challenge like time trial, sometimes it actually limits your choices to specific weapons or angles of approach but sort of works to keep things varied. And the whole sandboxy aspect is also what I liked.\n'Cause yeah lack of challenge, mostly in the fights (guards actually hit harder now and there's more of them, but conversely you get more efficient ways of killing them so it's still too easy), and feel of an interactive movie instead or something, is a beef I have with the series. I guess I embraced it though by now and even started to somewhat enjoy those overpowered fights. Still missing focus on stealth, but I don't mind it either anymore (I adjusted my expectations, eh? :D some missions ask you to remain undetected but stealth never seems to be the focus, really, you just charge head on or literally flick your fingers to kill every enemy on screen)\nYou still gotta love the parkour, rooftop jumping aspect, raiding tombs is fun too, there's a dash of puzzling involved tho not much, and story continuing present day and Ezio's day affairs still enjoyable, even though it doesn't really touch me deep on an emotional level.\nAbout the story... The side missions don't directly connect to the main arc of retrieving the \"magic apple\", they have more to do with Ezio going all \"I'm gonna pull the whole thing down. I'm gonna bring the whole f*n' diseased, corrupt temple down on your head\" on the Borgias or, rather, living in denial that he fudged up royally and instead explaining to everyone that you gotta have more systemic approach rather than playing the cutting-down-hydra's-heads game. Hence all the Rome rebuilding, winning minds of various factions and citizens etc.\nSo the main story may feel somewhat diluted and I guess people mostly enjoying the story aspect may be bit underwhelmed. Like I said, I personally didn't mind and actually like the game more even though it seems actually less focused on whole assassin's creed ordeal.\nOh, and Desmond Miles in present day finally gets some of focus and action, after all ac2 was supposed to prepare him for some parkouring in the present day so yeah, he gets some :3", "hours": 84.8, "username": "Blue Award", "products": 857, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 223, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-03-02", "text": "So, I know I dont really have that much time clocked in this game, just under 200 hours, but honestly, it's one of my favorites in the franchise. I've played all the games, I love them all in special ways, but Brotherhood just touches something within, the way not other games really can. The story is pretty solid, although it seems sometimes like theres just thrown-in filler missions but what can you expect?\nIt's a big game with a lot of stuff to do. Contracts, renovations, guild quests, the Leonardo missions, etc etc, and its easy (for me) to just play for hours and hours without really getting bored. I'm also really happy with the brotherhood part of this game, recruiting assassins throughout Rome...it seems symbolic, lol\nThe game seems kinda buggy sometimes (to be expected) and some of the collecting is...tedious, but this is still TOTALLY a worth-while game in the franchise and, in my honest opinion as a die-hard AC fan: It's most definitely one of the best games in the whole series and I totally reccomend it to anybody looking for a genuine AC experience.", "hours": 192.3, "username": "Notmilah", "products": 112, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 223, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-28", "text": "The story is pretty janky compared to AC2 but the city building aspect is much improved, as are the graphics. Lots of great additions but not enough to get me to want to finish everything at 100%.", "hours": 79.4, "username": "Sidotsy", "products": 527, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 223, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-23", "text": "Followed the series this far you should have no excuse playing this one as it is easily   the best in the series. Revolations is good but this one is a must have if you don't have this than you are not a true fan of the series.", "hours": 66.5, "username": "Misunderstood Wookiee", "products": 480, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 223, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-19", "text": "Assassin's Creed can be vaguely compared to the concept of 'The Matrix' in which you play a protagonist in the 'real world' who becomes someone else inside a 'virtual world'. It tells a fictional story of a war between Assassins and Templars - and spans across several real life historic periods. The franchise is one of few - which tells a massive story back-to-back instead of switching main characters half way through or making massive time jumps. Awesome franchise!", "hours": 34.8, "username": "Vendrium", "products": 819, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-14", "text": "GTA in the middle ages!", "hours": 32.0, "username": "Discovisi", "products": 425, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-14", "text": "Of the 3 Ezio Assassin's Creed game, this is the one that is the best executed. If you're only going to play one of the three, this is the one to play.", "hours": 29.8, "username": "jexreffy", "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-13", "text": "Assassin\u2019s Creed: Brotherhood is a direct continuation of Assassin\u2019s Creed II, in pretty much every sense. The story picks up exactly where the last one left off (both in the past and the present), and the game mechanics are more or less identical. In some ways, the need for this game to exist seems a bit unnecessary (i.e. it feels more like the result of a corporate mandate to make an annual franchise than a creative decision). That said, it\u2019s forgivable if only for the fact that it\u2019s just as good as its predecessor, if not better. Part of what feels forced is the contrived story revolving around Ezio losing his Apple of Eden and having to retrieve it. But there you go... it is what it is - basically, a flimsy excuse to move to a new setting and do more cool things with a well-loved character.\nThe game takes place in the early 1500s, almost entirely in Rome. While that may sound like a reduced scope in setting from the prior games, it\u2019s actually not. Rome is huge. Like, really huge. There are also a few other places that you get to explore in some of the main story missions as well, so there is plenty of variety in the environments. As usual, it\u2019s a lot of fun just to explore the city and discover its secrets. Brotherhood also greatly expands the role of horses (you can ride them pretty much anywhere), and there are some fun combat mechanics added as well. The missions in the game are similar to those from AC2, so nothing major has changed on that front. The other primary mechanics introduced in AC2 (notoriety, blending, etc) all return here as well and are also just as good.\nThe main addition this game brings to the series is the titular Brotherhood. Ezio can now recruit citizens to the Assassin Brotherhood. As you progress through the game, more recruit slots are unlocked. Once recruited, you can call your Assassins to assist in combat or send them on missions in a sort of optional sub-game. Doing either of these things awards XP to the recruits and eventually they level up and become more powerful. Though hardly revelatory by any means, it\u2019s a fun new aspect to the game and is a welcome addition.\nWhile Assassin\u2019s Creed: Brotherhood doesn\u2019t really do anything groundbreaking or expand on the established formula in any major way, it is still worth playing if you enjoyed AC2. While it is essentially more of the same, at least it\u2019s a *good* more of the same.\nGrade: A-\nNote: I don\u2019t recommend playing any of the Assassin\u2019s Creed games unless you have an Xbox360 controller (or equivalent-featured gamepad). The AC games have complicated control schemes and were clearly designed with controllers in mind, so proceed with mouse/keyboard at your own risk.", "hours": 55.0, "username": "noibn", "products": 1828, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-12", "text": "Not the innovation that the second game was, but still a great AC game with plenty of new features. Ezio once again proves himself to be a fun and interesting character to play as. The big draw-in on this one however is the Multiplayer. A fun and challenging type of gameplay where you and other players compete in a game of hide and seek. Hide in the crowd or run across rooftops to find and dispatch your target. Confrontations are quick, brutal and immensely satisfying!", "hours": 66.5, "user_id": "76561198027633888", "username": "Revan", "products": 177, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-09", "text": "Do you think you are a true assassin?\nThis is so far my favorite AC game. It introduces many new things that AC 2 didn't have, while still giving the same feel of being stealthy and awesome. You can hide behind corners, on top of buildings, and assassinate targets without even alerting a bug. After completing the game, I was left with many things to do, but instead I decided to move on to Revelations. I hope it offers as much excitement as this game has!", "hours": 15.4, "user_id": "76561198072370940", "username": "King Samuel", "products": 279, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-04", "text": "A great continuation of Ezio's Story! Rome is beautiful and worth spending time exploring. There's a really good mix of gameplay elements from AC2 and new loot, combat animations, & economics.\nHighest recommendation!", "hours": 108.5, "user_id": "76561198045618461", "username": "Deathwurm102", "products": 131, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-02-03", "text": "GG! :D Continues the story of Ezio Auditore in his quest against the Templar scum. The Assassin's liberate the city from the hands of the church. Many cool additions since AC2 such as having assassin's do your bidding, new weapons like a crossbow, better ways of getting around Rome via fast travel, etc. improves upon every aspect of AC2. Now I can't wait to get AC:R then AC3 but when they are on sale like this one was. :)", "hours": 37.8, "username": "IchibanPancakes", "products": 253, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-20", "text": "Another improvement over the previous game, and continues to wonderfully scratch the \"Tomb Raider itch\".  A huge amount of things to do and manage, a giant city to run around in, buildings to climb, etc, as well as a neat historic setting peppered with plenty of information on buildings, people and events.\nThere are problems of course, the controls don't always respond as quickly as you might like, the 100% synch challenges are more annoying than challenging, the investment system is a drag, and the scenes outside of the Animus continue to feel like irritating distractions to the \"real\" story of Ezio's adventures in Rome.  But they're minor problems in what is otherwise an extremely engaging game.", "hours": 38.9, "username": "MisterBlister", "products": 291, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 8, "recommended": false, "date": "2013-01-20", "text": "Assassin's Creed 2.5: Rome Edition", "hours": 2.3, "username": "Cameltoe Rodeo", "products": 414, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 224, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-18", "text": "Picks up exactly where Assassins Creed II left off, and for a side game theres a LOT to do, much more then AC II, the plot thickens as Ezio finds himself bearing down on the Borgia, and a few unexpected plot twists.\nIf youve played AC II and havent played this, I strongly recommend you play it, you wont regret it.", "hours": 32.1, "username": "Maverick", "products": 285, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-18", "text": "Picks up exactly where Assassins Creed II left off, and for a side game theres a LOT to do, much more then AC II, the plot thickens as Ezio finds himself bearing down on the Borgia, and a few unexpected plot twists.\nIf youve played AC II and havent played this, I strongly recommend you play it, you wont regret it.", "hours": 32.1, "username": "Maverick", "products": 285, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-18", "text": "This game is packed with endless side missions, quests, and features. It brings back the best of everything from its two predecessors and adds its own improvements. If Brotherhood has any weakness worth mentioning, it it's that the main story loses a bit of steam in the middle; with all the other stuff to do, though, you probably won't care.", "hours": 60.1, "username": "rpundurs", "products": 291, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 2, "recommended": false, "date": "2013-01-11", "text": "A fast made \"add-on\" to make money!\nMany bugs and the end is such not understandable only made to buy the next part of Assassin's Creed.\nAfter 50% the game can be finished. The other 50% you play Grand Theft HORSE!\nSteal horses, expand your gang, spend money in your bordels and other city attractions.\nSenseless killing and always blinding lights.", "hours": 25.8, "username": "Ni\u2020oXo\u2020i\u0418", "products": 690, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-10", "text": "Yet again, Ubisoft delivered; my favorite Assassin's Creed entry to date. New gameplay elements, faster gameplay, better graphics, incredible soundtrack, and of course, more conspiracies make this for an awesome Assassin's Creed game. I had mixed feelings when they announced multiplayer but they proved me wrong for the 2nd time (Splinter Cell Spies vs Mercs anyone?). UNIQUE multiplayer component that's second to none and interweaves flawlessly with the campaign storyline. Highly recommended.", "hours": 48.3, "username": "Hellspawn", "products": 194, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-08", "text": "Did you like Assassin's Creed II? Cool, this is exactly the same. Still fun, though.", "hours": 24.0, "username": "Chandler", "products": 1485, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-08", "text": "The 3rd game of the franchise and it further adds to the franchise by adding more features. Amazingly, the added features make a lot of sense if you consider the story.\nThe story is amazing and incredible for this franchise.\nAs usual, the cinematics, graphics and sounds are incredible and immerse you deeply into the game.\nA must-buy IP for gamers.", "hours": 62.7, "user_id": "76561198010479045", "username": "Peter Pan", "products": 176, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-06", "text": "The best of the Assassin's Creed 2 trilogy, and probably the best of the entire series. Too bad the multiplayer is dead on PC :(.", "hours": 44.7, "username": "[LUE] SwiftCrack", "products": 1463, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-03", "text": "Adult Ezio returns with even more epicness. If you enjoyed Assassin's Creed 2, there is not a single reason why you should hold back from buying this one. The plethora of new features can be overwhelming at first, but once you get the hang of it you won't want to put it down. The storyline in the Assassin's Creed games gets better and better as a new game is added to the series. Brotherhood is no exception. WIth the added multiplayer feature of Brotherhood, you won't be leaving your room for a while. The multiplayer adds a lot more to the game with a system that rewards you with items and perks as you level up. Buy it.", "hours": 111.0, "username": "Rube", "products": 128, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2013-01-03", "text": "I can say without hesitation that Brotherhood is easily the best installment out of the entire Assassin's Creed franchise. Ubisoft Montreal took the massive breakthrough that was AC2's gameplay and refined it, expanded it, and built on top of it - giving the player an experience with an immense amount of depth and ceaseless enjoyment.\nWhile some might say that this game was more \"expansion\" than a true release the continuation of Ezio Auditore's storyline did wonders for the character, the historical time period, and the AC universe in general.\nBrotherhood was also the first title in the series to feature an online multiplayer that not only amazed us with its addictiveness but also really challenged us - rewarding players for being patient and clever instead of relentless and clumsy.", "hours": 38.6, "user_id": "76561198006893472", "username": "Fear2288", "products": 418, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 225, "page_order": 9, "recommended": false, "date": "2012-12-31", "text": "I don't no why they like it, expectually on PC", "hours": 0.7, "username": "A7MADoZ", "products": 104, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 226, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-29", "text": "Epic Awesomness!", "hours": 19.6, "username": "moonsquid", "products": 523, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "48190", "page": 226, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-29", "text": "How can one say no to an Assassin's Creed game!", "hours": 1.5, "username": "tehTiruviel", "products": 653, "early_access": false}
